+{"parentUuid":"df6036c5-a436-4ccc-b596-e7a72c5b252d","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/workspace","sessionId":"eb2ddc5c-1d90-41a8-94e4-8ecbf20b60da","version":"2.1.63","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"logical-wondering-puzzle","type":"progress","data":{"message":{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BxksrAkH1kFFkiaH3DFgXb","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Factory Reset\n     2→\n     3→Solve button-toggle puzzles for a factory machine control panel.\n     4→\n     5→## Part 1: Toggle Puzzle\n     6→\n     7→A machine has N lights, all initially **off** (false). There are M buttons. Each button, when pressed, **toggles** a specific set of lights (off→on, on→off). Each button can be pressed **at most once** (0 or 1 presses).\n     8→\n     9→Find the minimum set of buttons to press so that the lights match a target configuration.\n    10→\n    11→### Data Model\n    12→\n    13→```typescript\n    14→interface Machine {\n    15→  target: boolean[];     // desired state for each light (all start off)\n    16→  buttons: number[][];   // buttons[i] = array of light indices toggled by button i\n    17→}\n    18→```\n    19→\n    20→### API\n    21→\n    22→```typescript\n    23→function solveToggle(machine: Machine): number[] | null;\n    24→```\n    25→\n    26→- Return an array of **button indices** (0-based) to press, sorted in ascending order.\n    27→- If multiple solutions exist, return the one with the **fewest button presses**.\n    28→- If tied on press count, return the **lexicographically smallest** set of indices.\n    29→- Return `null` if no solution exists.\n    30→\n    31→### Example\n    32→\n    33→```\n    34→Lights: 4 (indices 0-3), all start off\n    35→Target: [true, true, false, true]\n    36→Buttons:\n    37→  0: toggles lights [0, 1]\n    38→  1: toggles lights [1, 2, 3]\n    39→  2: toggles lights [0, 3]\n    40→\n    41→Press buttons 0 and 1:\n    42→  Button 0: lights become [on, on, off, off]\n    43→  Button 1: lights become [on, off, on, on]\n    44→  Wait — that gives [true, false, true, true], not the target.\n    45→\n    46→Press buttons 1 and 2:\n    47→  Button 1: [off, on, on, on]\n    48→  Button 2: [on, on, on, off]\n    49→  That gives [true, true, true, false], also wrong.\n    50→\n    51→Press buttons 0, 1, 2:\n    52→  After 0: [on, on, off, off]\n    53→  After 1: [on, off, on, on]\n    54→  After 2: [off, off, on, off]\n    55→  Wrong again.\n    56→\n    57→Correct: press buttons 0 and 2:\n    58→  After 0: [on, on, off, off]\n    59→  After 2: [off, on, off, on]\n    60→  Result: [false, true, false, true]\n    61→  Hmm, that's not the target either.\n    62→\n    63→Actually, let's re-check: target is [true, true, false, true].\n    64→  Press button 2: toggles [0, 3] → [on, off, off, on]\n    65→  Press button 1: toggles [1, 2, 3] → [on, on, on, off]\n    66→  Not matching.\n    67→\n    68→  Press button 0: toggles [0, 1] → [on, on, off, off]\n    69→  Press button 1: toggles [1, 2, 3] → [on, off, on, on]\n    70→  Press button 2: toggles [0, 3] → [off, off, on, off]\n    71→  Still wrong.\n    72→\n    73→The toggle order doesn't matter (toggling is commutative). So for target [T, T, F, T]:\n    74→We need light 0=on, 1=on, 2=off, 3=on.\n    75→Button 0 affects {0,1}, Button 1 affects {1,2,3}, Button 2 affects {0,3}.\n    76→We need: b0 XOR b2 = 1 (light 0), b0 XOR b1 = 1 (light 1), b1 = 0 (light 2), b1 XOR b2 = 1 (light 3).\n    77→From light 2: b1=0. From light 1: b0=1. From light 0: b2=0. Check light 3: 0 XOR 0 = 0 ≠ 1. No solution!\n    78→\n    79→solveToggle returns null.\n    80→```\n    81→\n    82→**Constraint**: Must handle up to 40 buttons and 40 lights and return results in under 5 seconds. Brute-force enumeration of all 2^40 button combinations is not feasible.\n    83→\n    84→## Part 2: Counter Puzzle\n    85→\n    86→A variant where lights are replaced by **counters**. Each counter starts at 0. Buttons **increment** (not toggle) specific counters by 1. Counters wrap around at a given modulus (e.g., mod 5 means values cycle 0→1→2→3→4→0).\n    87→\n    88→Each button can be pressed **multiple times** (0 to modulus-1 times).\n    89→\n    90→```typescript\n    91→function solveCounter(\n    92→  lights: number[],      // target counter values (each 0..modulus-1)\n    93→  buttons: number[][],   // buttons[i] = indices of counters affected\n    94→  modulus: number        // counters wrap at this value (always prime)\n    95→): number[] | null;\n    96→```\n    97→\n    98→- Return an array where `result[i]` is the number of times button `i` should be pressed (0 to modulus-1).\n    99→- If multiple solutions exist, return the one with the **minimum total presses** (sum of all result values).\n   100→- If tied on total, return the **lexicographically smallest** result array.\n   101→- Return `null` if no solution exists.\n   102→- The modulus is always a **prime number**.\n   103→\n   104→**Constraint**: Must handle up to 40 buttons, 40 counters, and modulus up to 97. Must complete in under 5 seconds.\n   105→\n   106→## Commands\n   107→\n   108→```bash\n   109→npm test        # run tests\n   110→npm run build   # compile TypeScript\n   111→npm run lint    # lint source\n   112→```\n   113→\n   114→## File Structure\n   115→\n   116→Place your implementation in `src/`. The main entry point should be `src/index.ts`.\n   117→"}]},"uuid":"c2584eb3-f1c5-4c42-b709-419968de8469","timestamp":"2026-03-10T03:59:51.989Z"},"normalizedMessages":[],"type":"agent_progress","prompt":"","agentId":"a97a57bd1fc30d125"},"toolUseID":"agent_msg_01QjcRXAych95CHFg2ud53dD","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01RpgJ3aMQ76ZLn57K5ZxTQ2","uuid":"381f641b-55a0-48d5-a05e-1c874a9e4275","timestamp":"2026-03-10T03:59:52.165Z"}
