imum weight x, then lex smallest.\n\n  // Use Gaussian elimination on the augmented matrix [A^T | I] to find\n  // the row echelon form and identify free variables.\n\n  // Actually, let's think about this differently.\n  // We have n equations (one per light) and m unknowns (one per button).\n  // Each equation: sum of x_j for j in buttons affecting light i ≡ target[i] (mod 2)\n\n  // Represent each equation as a bitmask over the m buttons, plus target bit.\n  // Then do Gaussian elimination to reduce.\n\n  // Build matrix: rows = lights, cols = buttons\n  // row[i] has bit j set if button j affects light i\n  // augmented bit = target[i]\n\n  // Use BigInt for bitmasks since m can be up to 40\n  const rows: bigint[] = new Array(n);\n  const targetBits: number[] = new Array(n);\n\n  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n    let row = 0n;\n    for (let j = 0; j < m; j++) {\n      if (buttons[j].includes(i)) {\n        row |= 1n << BigInt(j);\n      }\n    }\n    rows[i] = row;\n    targetBits[i] = target[i] ? 1 : 0;\n  }\n\n  // Gaussian elimination over GF(2)\n  // We'll track pivot columns and reduce the system\n  const pivotRow: number[] = []; // pivotRow[col] = row index that has pivot at this column\n  const pivotCol: number[] = []; // ordered list of pivot columns\n  const usedRow = new Set<number>();\n\n  for (let col = 0; col < m; col++) {\n    // Find a row with a 1 in this column that hasn't been used as pivot\n    let found = -1;\n    for (let row = 0; row < n; row++) {\n      if (!usedRow.has(row) && ((rows[row] >> BigInt(col)) & 1n) === 1n) {\n        found = row;\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n    if (found === -1) continue; // free variable\n\n    usedRow.add(found);\n    pivotCol.push(col);\n    pivotRow.push(found);\n\n    // Eliminate this column from all other rows\n    for (let row = 0; row < n; row++) {\n      if (row !== found && ((rows[row] >> BigInt(col)) & 1n) === 1n) {\n        rows[row] ^= rows[found];\n        targetBits[row] ^= targetBits[found];\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Check consistency: any row that's all zeros but target is 1 means no solution\n  for (let row = 0; row < n; row++) {\n    if (rows[row] === 0n && targetBits[row] === 1) {\n      return null;\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Now we have a reduced system. Pivot columns are determined by free variables.\n  // Free variables are columns not in pivotCol.\n  const pivotColSet = new Set(pivotCol);\n  const freeVars: number[] = [];\n  for (let col = 0; col < m; col++) {\n    if (!pivotColSet.has(col)) {\n      freeVars.push(col);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // For each assignment of free variables, compute the determined variables\n  // and find the solution with minimum weight, then lex smallest.\n  // Number of free variables can be up to 40, so we can't enumerate all 2^40.\n  // But in practice, with up to 40 buttons and 40 lights, the number of free\n  // variables should be manageable... actually it could be up to 40.\n\n  // We need a smarter approach. Let's think about this as an optimization problem.\n  // After GE, each pivot variable is determined by the free variables:\n  //   x_pivot = target_pivot XOR (sum of coefficients * free vars)\n  // We want to minimize the total number of 1s across all variables.\n\n  // Build the dependency: for each pivot variable, express it in terms of free vars.\n  // pivotCol[k] is determined by pivotRow[k]:\n  //   x_{pivotCol[k]} = targetBits[pivotRow[k]] XOR (XOR of x_j for j in freeVars where row has bit j)\n\n  // Create a mapping: for each pivot, the set of free variables it depends on\n  const pivotDeps: bigint[] = new Array(pivotCol.length); // bitmask over freeVars indices\n  const pivotConst: number[] = new Array(pivotCol.length);\n\n  for (let k = 0; k < pivotCol.length; k++) {\n    const row = pivotRow[k];\n    let deps = 0n;\n    for (let fi = 0; fi < freeVars.length; fi++) {\n      if ((rows[row] >> BigInt(freeVars[fi]) & 1n) === 1n) {\n        deps |= 1n << BigInt(fi);\n      }\n    }\n    pivotDeps[k] = d