nt, b: bigint, m: number): number {\n  // Compare two solutions lexicographically by their button index sets.\n  // The lex smallest set is determined by comparing from the smallest index.\n  // Actually, for sets: {0,2} < {1} because we compare element by element.\n  // A set with a smaller first element is lex smaller. If same first, compare second, etc.\n  // Equivalently, compare the bitmasks: extract bits from LSB.\n  // The set with fewer elements when both have same first element... it's complex.\n  //\n  // Lex comparison of sorted arrays: compare element by element.\n  // {0, 2} vs {1}: 0 < 1, so {0,2} is smaller.\n  // {0, 2} vs {0, 1}: 0==0, then 2 > 1, so {0,1} is smaller.\n  // {0} vs {0, 1}: 0==0, then {0} has no more elements, so {0} is smaller.\n  //\n  // Given bitmasks, compare from LSB:\n  // Find the lowest bit where they differ.\n  const diff = a ^ b;\n  if (diff === 0n) return 0;\n  // Lowest differing bit\n  const lowestDiff = diff & (-diff);\n  // If a has this bit set but b doesn't: a has an extra element at this position\n  // If it's in a but not b:\n  //   - If a has more 1s below this position... no, the bits below are the same.\n  //   All bits below lowestDiff are the same in a and b.\n  //   At lowestDiff: one has it, the other doesn't.\n  //   The one that has the smaller set at this point depends:\n  //   - If a has it (and b doesn't): a includes this button index but b doesn't.\n  //     For lex comparison of sets: having an extra element earlier...\n  //     Wait, we need to be more careful.\n  //\n  //   Actually, lex comparison of sorted arrays:\n  //   Let's think about it as: build the sorted arrays and compare.\n  //   Since bits are from position 0 upward, the sorted array is just the set bits in order.\n  //\n  //   At the lowest differing bit position p:\n  //   - All elements below p are the same in both sets (since lower bits are identical)\n  //   - One set has p, the other doesn't\n  //   - If a has p and b doesn't: a'